        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 25<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Galton</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your few words of congratulation have given me sincere pleasure &amp; I thank you cordially.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have been still better pleased, if you had told me how you were. I have enquired whenever I have had a chance of hearing, but did not hear some two months ago a very good account.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I trust &amp; hope by your note that you are well again, but I know that over mental work takes long in recovery.—</p>
<p>With hearty thanks &amp; good wishes | Yours very sincerely | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is conjectured by the references to Galton’s poor health and on the assumption that the letter alludes to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin’s</ref> success in the mathematical tripos at Cambridge (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5796.xml" resp="#automat" cert="medium">letter to G. H. Darwin, 24 January [1868]</ref> and n. 2).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The letter from Galton has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Galton suffered a breakdown in health in 1866 and did not recover fully until the beginning of 1869 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2852.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Gillham 2001</ref>, pp. 150–1).</note>
        </div>        
            
